'''Sebastian Matthew Berhalter''' (born May 10, 2001) is an American<!-- he's not notable for being British or Irish, see [[WP:CONTEXTBIO]] -->  professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

==Early life and college==
Sebastian Matthew Berhalter was born in [[London]] to Rosalind and [[Gregg Berhalter]], who at the time was a professional football player for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Sebastian Berhalter was raised in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. Between 2012 and 2013, he played youth football with Swedish club [[Hammarby Fotboll|Hammarby IF]] when his father managed their senior team.<ref name="hammarby">{{cite web|url=https://unicoach.se/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/unicoach2020-v5.pdf|title=Akademirapport: Säsongen 2020|publisher=Unicoach|date=April 8, 2021|access-date=June 13, 2021|language=Swedish}}</ref>

He joined the [[Columbus Crew]] youth academy<ref>{{Cite web |title=Columbus Crew |url=https://www.thecrewyouth.com/ |access-date=2025-11-24 |website=www.thecrewyouth.com}}</ref> in 2014, climbing the ranks and making 103 appearances and scoring 11 goals. In 2019, Berhalter played [[College soccer in the United States|college soccer]] for the [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's soccer|Tar Heels]] of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]], playing in 16 matches.<ref name="MLS-Signed"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Mendola |first=Nicholas |date=January 17, 2020 |title=Sebastian Berhalter signs Homegrown deal with Columbus Crew |url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2020/01/17/mls-sebastian-berhalter-columbus-crew-homegrown/ |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=July 11, 2020}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Columbus Crew===
Berhalter was announced as a [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player]] signing by the Columbus Crew of [[Major League Soccer]] on January 17, 2020.<ref name="MLS-Signed">{{cite news |last=Baer |first=Benjamin |date=January 17, 2020 |title=Columbus Crew SC sign Sebastian Berhalter, Gregg's son, to Homegrown deal |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/01/17/columbus-crew-sc-sign-sebastian-berhalter-greggs-son-homegrown-deal |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=July 11, 2020}}</ref> He made his professional debut on July 11, 2020, against [[FC Cincinnati]] during the [[MLS is Back Tournament]] in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Quillen |first=Ian Nicholas |date=August 8, 2020 |title=Every Homegrown Player who made their debut at the MLS is Back Tournament |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/every-homegrown-player-who-made-their-debut-mls-back-tournament |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=January 24, 2025}}</ref> Berhalter made nine appearances for the Crew during the [[2020 MLS season|2020 season]], which ended in their [[MLS Cup 2020|MLS Cup]] victory.<ref name="TCP-2023">{{cite news |date=December 6, 2023 |title=Whitecaps sign midfielder Sebastian Berhalter through 2025 MLS season |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/whitecaps-sign-midfielder-sebastian-berhalter-through-2025-mls-season/article_89058a21-e452-5af4-9359-6bb4c3e07e1c.html |work=[[Toronto Star]] |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |accessdate=January 24, 2025}}</ref>

====Austin FC (loan)====
On March 3, 2021, Berhalter joined Major League Soccer club [[Austin FC]] on loan for the [[2021 Major League Soccer season|2021 season]].<ref>{{cite web |date=March 3, 2021 |title=Austin FC Acquires 19-Year-Old Midfielder Sebastian Berhalter on Loan Ahead of 2021 MLS Season |url=https://www.austinfc.com/post/2021/03/03/austin-fc-acquires-19-year-old-midfielder-sebastian-berhalter-loan-ahead-2021-mls |website=AustinFC.com |accessdate=March 3, 2021 |archive-date=April 18, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210418235000/https://www.austinfc.com/post/2021/03/03/austin-fc-acquires-19-year-old-midfielder-sebastian-berhalter-loan-ahead-2021-mls |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his debut for the club on April 24 against the [[Colorado Rapids]], coming on as a substitute in the 3–1 away victory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colorado Rapids 1–3 Austin FC |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2021/04/25/united-states/mls/colorado-rapids/austin/3471822/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> Following the 2021 season, Berhalter's contract option was declined by Austin and he returned to Columbus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinfc.com/news/austin-fc-announce-roster-decisions-ahead-of-2022-season|title=Austin FC Announce Roster Decisions Ahead of 2022 Season &#124; Austin FC|website=austinfc}}</ref>

===Vancouver Whitecaps FC===
On February 4, 2022, Berhalter was traded to [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] in exchange for $50,000 in [[general allocation money]] and an additional $50,000 should certain conditions be met.<ref>{{Cite news |date=February 4, 2022 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/vancouver-whitecaps-acquire-midfielder-sebastian-berhalter-in-trade-with-columbu |title=Vancouver Whitecaps acquire midfielder Sebastian Berhalter in trade with Columbus Crew |website=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=March 1, 2022}}</ref>

During the [[2023 Major League Soccer season|2023 season]], he made 37 appearances for the Whitecaps and scored two goals across all competitions.<ref name="TCP-2023"/>

During the [[2024 Major League Soccer season|2024 season]], he made 45 appearances, had 6 assists,<ref name="Vancouver Whitecaps Scoring Stats">{{Cite web |title=Vancouver Whitecaps Scoring Stats |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/team/stats/_/id/9727 |access-date=2025-11-24 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> and scored three goals across all competitions.<ref name="Vancouver Whitecaps Scoring Stats"/>

During the [[2025 Major League Soccer season|2025 season]], Berhalter played 33 games and scored four goals. He became the top ranked player on his team for assists with 12 assists during the season.<ref name="Vancouver Whitecaps Scoring Stats"/> Additionally, Berhalter appeared the in 2025 [[MLS All-Star Game]] against the [[Liga MX|LIGA MX]] All-Stars team on July 23, 2025, which MLS won 3-1.<ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=2025 MLS All-Star Game {{!}} Latest {{!}} mlssoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/allstar/2025/en/ |access-date=2025-11-24 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref>

== International career ==
[[File:Sebastian Berhalter, 2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup, 01 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Berhalter with the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].]]

On May 22, 2025, Berhalter was called up by [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] coach [[Mauricio Pochettino]] for training camp in Chicago ahead of matches against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 22, 2025 |title=Pochettino Names 27-Player Roster for Training Camp ahead of June Matches Against Turkey and Switzerland |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2025/05/mauricio-pochettino-27-player-roster-training-camp-june-matches-turkey-switzerland |access-date=May 22, 2025 |website=[[United States Soccer Federation]]}}</ref> He made his debut in the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=June 27, 2025 |title=He was raised alongside the U.S. men's national team. Now he's part of it. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2025/06/27/sebastian-berhalter-usmnt/|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 4, 2025}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the national team during the U.S.' 5–1 thumping of [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at [[Raymond James Stadium]] in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-19 |title=WATCH: Sebastian Berhalter nets first USMNT goal and sets up Alex Freeman's first international goal on two stunning set pieces {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/watch-sebastian-berhalter-nets-first-usmnt-goal-and-sets-up-alex-freeman-s-first-international-goal-on-two-stunning-set-pieces/bltbbfa95ef6e251abe |access-date=2025-11-19 |website=www.goal.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Abnos |first=Alexander |date=2025-11-19 |title=USMNT dominate first-choice Uruguay 5-1, a long-awaited signature win |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/18/usmnt-uruguay-friendly-sebastian-berhalter-alex-freeman |access-date=2025-11-19 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-19 |title='No regular players' - Sebastian Berhalter and Alex Freeman shine as Mauricio Pochettino emphatically shows the USMNT is bigger than any single name: Winners and losers from the win over Uruguay {{!}} Goal.com English Oman |url=https://www.goal.com/en-om/lists/usmnt-winners-losers-uruguay-berhalter-alex-freeman-mauricio-pochettino/bltcb53c0e30d411e62 |access-date=2025-11-19 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-OM}}</ref>

==Personal life==
He is the son of current [[Chicago Fire FC]] and former [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] head coach [[Gregg Berhalter]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/governance/board-of-directors/us-soccer-president-cindy-parlow-cone/remarks-introducing-new-us-soccer-mnt-head-coach-gregg-berhalter-december-4-2018|title=Remarks Introducing New US Soccer MNT Head Coach Gregg Berhalter December 4 2018|website=www.ussoccer.com|accessdate=March 1, 2022}}</ref> and former [[University of North Carolina Tar Heels]] player Rosalind "Roz" Berhalter, who won four national championships.<ref>{{Cite web |title=DI Women's Soccer Championship History {{!}} NCAA.com |url=https://www.ncaa.com/history/soccer-women/d1 |access-date=2025-11-24 |website=www.ncaa.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Sebastian Berhalter - Men's Soccer |url=https://goheels.com/sports/mens-soccer/roster/sebastian-berhalter/16401 |access-date=2025-02-09 |website=University of North Carolina Athletics |language=en}}</ref>

Berhalter also holds Irish citizenship, which was obtained through family ancestry.

